ard engineers. Delve into statistics and recovery policies to learn how farming was rescued and revived, amid fears for post-war national food security. Trist's heartfelt writing, astute observations and reflections, on this historically significant event reveal resilience and raise questions about governmental and personal responsibilities in climate crises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFloodszEnglandzSuffolkxHistory. 4aBritish Local History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  a1950s Suffolk farmer.  a1950s Suffolk.  a1950s disaster planning.  a1950s farmers in Suffolk.  a1950s farming.  aAerial survey of East Suffolk coast.  aBritish natural disasters.  aFlood compensation.  aHistoric uses of Suffolk marshes.  aHistory of catchment boards in Suffolk.  aHistory of county agricultural executive committees (CAEC).  aMaps of East Coast flooding.  aMemoirs of public servants.  aMinistry of Agriculture and River Boards.  aNational Agricultural Advisory Service (NAAS).  aNorth sea floods and farming.  aOfficial reports on coastal flooding.  aPost-war agricultural policy.  aReclamation of marshland.  aSuffolk diaries.  aSuffolk environmental history.  aThe great tide in Suffolk.  aattle of the breaches.1 aParkinson, Denise, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311143096640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805432685?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805432685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805432685/original  a978-3-11-143096-6  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles